diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as oral ulcers, alopecia, leukopenia (a drop in white blood cell count), nephritis (inflammation of the kidneys), and acute pericarditis (inflammation of the pericardium).

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease shares features of several connective tissue diseases including SLE, and can present with nephritis, acute pericarditis, oral ulcers, alopecia, and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.rationale: While RA is primarily known for joint inflammation, it can also manifest systemic symptoms including leukopenia, pericarditis, and in severe cases, kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disorder primarily affects the salivary and lacrimal glands causing dry mouth and eyes, but can also cause kidney disease (nephritis), and leukopenia. Oral ulcers and alopecia are less common but possible manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This condition is characterized by oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and often involves inflammation of various parts of the body including the skin (alopecia), eyes, and occasionally the heart (pericarditis) and kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus
diagnoses.rationale: Some drugs can induce lupus-like symptoms including alopecia, pericarditis, leukopenia, nephritis, and oral ulcers, which usually improve upon discontinuation of the offending drug.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.rationale: This rare vasculitis can affect kidneys (causing nephritis), the skin (leading to ulcers and alopecia), and rarely, the heart (causing pericarditis). Leukopenia is less common.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. While oral ulcers and nephritis are less common, it can sometimes cause alopecia, and in severe cases, myocarditis that may mimic pericarditis symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: A group of disorders that destroy blood vessels by inflammation. Depending on the specific type, vasculitis can cause symptoms like nephritis, pericarditis, and, less frequently, leukopenia, oral ulcers, and alopecia.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: In advanced stages, HIV can cause a wide range of symptoms due to its immunosuppressive nature, including leukopenia, oral ulcers, and indirectly causing or worsening conditions like nephritis. Pericarditis and alopecia are less directly associated but can occur.

diagnoses: Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS) syndrome
Evans syndrome (autoimmune hemolytic anemia with thrombocytopenia)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect multiple systems including the nervous system (seizures), kidneys (nephritis), and heart (pericarditis and pericardial effusion), often accompanied by fever.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.rationale: Rheumatic fever can cause inflammation in various parts of the body, including the heart (pericarditis), can lead to nephritis, and might be preceded by fever. Seizures are less common but can occur due to inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Infective endocarditis can cause pericarditis and pericardial effusion due to its proximity; fever is a common symptom. While nephritis and seizures are less typical, they can occur due to complications like emboli or immune complex deposition.

diagnoses.name: Viral Myocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Commonly caused by Coxsackievirus, it presents with pericarditis, pericardial effusion, and can include symptoms like fever. Seizures and nephritis might be observed in severe systemic cases.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Autoimmune conditions, apart from SLE, can cause acute pericarditis, pericardial effusion, fever, and potentially involve the kidneys, leading to nephritis. CNS involvement could explain seizures.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculous Pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, presenting with pericarditis, pericardial effusion, fever, and can affect the kidneys. Central nervous system involvement can lead to seizures.

diagnoses.name: Uremic Pericarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Occurs in patients with severe uremia (often due to worsening nephritis), leading to pericarditis and pericardial effusion. Fever can be present, and seizures might occur due to uremic encephalopathy.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD includes features of various systemic autoimmune diseases and can present with fever, nephritis, pericarditis, pericardial effusion, and potentially seizures due to neurological involvement.

diagnoses.name: Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.rationale: This condition follows a streptococcal infection, potentially presenting with nephritis, fever, and could indirectly lead to pericarditis and pericardial effusion. Seizures could occur in severe, complicated cases.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: A multi-system inflammatory disease that can involve the heart (pericarditis, pericardial effusion), kidneys (nephritis), cause fever, and potentially affect the nervous system, resulting in seizures.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can damage any part of the body, including skin, joints, and/or organs inside the body.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. It can affect the skin, joints, heart, and the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to numerous signs and symptoms, including mouth and genital ulcers, and eye problems.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus/acquired immunodeficiency syndrome – a virus that damages the immune system and weakens the body's ability to fight everyday infections and disease.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A potentially serious infectious bacterial disease that mainly affects the lungs.

diagnoses.name: Malignancies
diagnoses.description: Cancers affecting various parts of the body, which can cause systemic symptoms including weight loss, fever, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection usually spread by sexual contact that starts as a painless sore.

diagnoses.name: Churg-Strauss Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Also known as Eosinophilic Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (EGPA), is a rare autoimmune condition that causes inflammation of small and medium-sized blood vessels (vasculitis) in persons with a history of asthma or allergies.

diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with widespread symptoms, including hematological disorders (e.g., leukopenia), neurological symptoms (e.g., cognitive dysfunctions), and can indirectly affect fertility.
MS can lead to neurological symptoms that affect vision (optic neuritis) and cognitive functions, potentially exacerbating or mimicking obsessive-compulsive behavior.
CKD can lead to various systemic manifestations including urinary tract infections due to decreased immunity, and it can indirectly impact fertility.
Diabetes can cause complications such as urinary tract infections due to high blood sugar levels, affect vision (diabetic retinopathy), and impact the immune system (leukopenia).
HIV/AIDS can lead to leukopenia due to its impact on the immune system, and can indirectly influence fertility. It can also be associated with a range of neuropsychiatric conditions.
Thyroid dysfunctions can impact mental health (including obsessive behavior), affect vision, and have implications on fertility.
RA, an autoimmune disease, can present with systemic symptoms impacting multiple body systems, including hematological (leukopenia) and can have ocular manifestations.
Anxiety can manifest with obsessive-compulsive behaviors and somatic symptoms, which might include difficulty focusing vision due to stress.
PCOS is a direct cause of infertility in women and can also be associated with psychological symptoms, although it does not directly cause leukopenia or UTIs.

Depression might not directly cause all the symptoms but can exacerbate or contribute to a person’s perception of physical health problems, including obsessive-compulsive behaviors and difficulties with cognition and vision focus.

diagnoses.name: Oral thrush

diagnoses.name: Stress or anxiety disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Stress can exacerbate or trigger symptoms like hyperactivity and blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Viral infections
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain viral infections can cause lymphadenitis and might also lead to mouth ulcers or patches resembling leukoplakia.

diagnoses.name: Benign essential blepharospasm
diagnoses.reasoning: A condition possibly explaining the occurrence of blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Commonly causes lymphadenitis and might induce oral hairy leukoplakia in immunocompromised individuals.

diagnoses.name: Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Could explain hyperactivity, with other symptoms being unrelated or secondary.

diagnoses.name: Lichen planus
diagnoses.reasoning: Might present with leukoplakia-like lesions in the mouth and could be associated with dermal symptoms similar to dyshydrotic eczema.

diagnoses.name: Atopic dermatitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Could contribute to or exacerbate dyshydrotic eczema and related skin conditions.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: In advanced stages, can lead to immunosuppression allowing for oral hairy leukoplakia, chronic eczema, and recurrent infections causing lymphadenitis.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often features symptoms including dry eyes and periodontal disease, among others.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.description: Elevated blood sugar levels can lead to a wide range of symptoms including urinary tract infections and periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can have systemic effects, indirectly causing various symptoms such as Sjögren's Syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Chemical Sensitivity
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by severe allergic-like reactions to many different kinds of pollutants including smoke, pesticides, plastics, synthetic fabrics, scented products, petroleum products, and paints.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that worsens with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest. It can be associated with a wide array of symptoms including chemical sensitivities.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Patients often report sensitivity to chemicals.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs, and may cause varied symptoms similar to those mentioned.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: Thyroid hormone deficiency can result in a wide variety of symptoms, including dry skin, fatigue, and sensitivity to cold. These phenomena could indirectly mediate some of the symptoms listed.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin Deficiencies
diagnoses.description: Deficiencies in vitamins such as B12, Vitamin D, and others can lead to a range of symptoms including chemical sensitivities and dysosmia.

diagnoses.name: Environmental Allergies
diagnoses.description: Allergic reactions to various environmental substances can cause symptoms such as dysosmia and chemical sensitivities.

diagnoses.description: Stress or Anxiety
diagnoses.rationale: Stress and anxiety can manifest through various physical symptoms, including muscle tension leading to pain (which might be interpreted as vulvodynia), difficulty focusing vision, and immune system disruptions potentially causing leukocytosis. Psychological stress can also exacerbate conditions like periodontal disease and alopecia.

diagnoses.description: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.rationale: Certain autoimmune disorders can cause a wide array of symptoms due to the immune system attacking the body's own cells. This can lead to conditions such as alopecia (hair loss), leukocytosis (as the body's response to what it mistakenly perceives as pathogens), periodontal disease, and pain syndromes such as vulvodynia.

diagnoses.description: Hormonal Imbalances
diagnoses.rationale: Hormonal imbalances, including thyroid disorders, can lead to a multitude of symptoms. Hypothyroidism, for example, can cause hair loss (alopecia), menstrual irregularities that might exacerbate vulvodynia, and can impact immune function (possibly affecting white blood cell counts and periodontal health).

diagnoses.description: Nutritional Deficiencies
diagnoses.rationale: Deficiencies in essential nutrients, such as iron, vitamin B12, and vitamin D, can lead to symptoms like alopecia, immune system dysregulation (affecting leukocyte levels and potentially leading to leukocytosis), and periodontal disease. Severe deficiencies might also impact neurological function, contributing to difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.description: Chronic Inflammatory Conditions
diagnoses.rationale: Conditions with chronic inflammation, such as Crohn's disease or rheumatoid arthritis, could indirectly contribute to the listed symptoms. They can cause leukocytosis as the body responds to ongoing inflammation, contribute to nutritional deficiencies affecting oral health and hair, and cause widespread pain, possibly exacerbating conditions like vulvodynia.

diagnoses.description: Hypervitaminosis A
diagnoses.rationale: Excessive intake of vitamin A can lead to a range of symptoms including vision disturbances, hair loss (alopecia), and bone and muscle pain, which might be relevant to vulvodynia. It can also affect immune function, potentially contributing to leukocytosis.

diagnoses.description: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Uncontrolled diabetes can lead to a compromised immune system (potentially affecting leukocyte counts), worsen periodontal disease, contribute to alopecia, and cause neuropathy which might be confused with or exacerbate conditions like vulvodynia. Vision problems are also a common complication of diabetes.

diagnoses.description: Polyglandular Autoimmune Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This syndrome involves multiple endocrine organs' failure, which can lead to a combination of symptoms including alopecia, periodontal disease due to hormonal imbalances, and leukocytosis as part of the autoimmune response. It could also indirectly cause or worsen vulvodynia through other autoimmune mechanisms.

diagnoses.description: Lupus
diagnoses.rationale: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) can cause a wide variety of symptoms, including those listed, due to its systemic autoimmune nature. It can lead to leukocytosis, hair loss, oral ulcers or periodontal disease, and neuropathic pain, which might relate to vulvodynia.

diagnoses.description: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Lyme disease, caused by the Borrelia burgdorferi bacteria, can lead to a broad spectrum of symptoms if left untreated, including neurological problems (potentially affecting vision focus), arthritis (which could exacerbate pain conditions like vulvodynia), alopecia, and immune system responses such as leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus

diagnoses.name: Pelvic Inflammatory Disease

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection

diagnoses.name: Lupus

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: PCOS may relate indirectly to these symptoms through hormonal imbalances affecting the menstrual cycle, potentially exacerbating conditions like endometriosis.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden headache, weakness, confusion, and problems with speech and vision.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraine with aura is a common type of migraine. The aura usually precedes the headache phase and can include visual disturbances like scintillating scotomas, sensory symptoms, aphasia, and weakness. Hearing loss is less common but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is often labeled as a mini-stroke. It’s a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. TIA doesn’t cause permanent damage. It can produce symptoms like aphasia, weakness, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: Acoustic neuroma is a benign tumor that develops on the nerves that influence your balance and hearing leading from your inner ear to your brain. Common symptoms include hearing loss, tinnitus, and balance issues. Other neurological symptoms like headache can develop as the tumor grows.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause symptoms like numbness, weakness, balance issues, and in rare cases, hearing loss. Visual phenomena and headaches may also occur.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor refers to a collection, or mass, of abnormal cells in your brain. The symptoms can vary greatly and may include headache, hearing loss, speech difficulties like aphasia, weakness, and seizures, depending on the tumor's location.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: Meniere's disease affects the inner ear and can cause dizziness, tinnitus, hearing loss, and a feeling of pressure deep inside the ear. While other symptoms such as headache and aphasia are not directly related, they can be experienced concurrently due to discomfort or complications.

diagnoses.name: Neurosyphilis
diagnoses.description: Neurosyphilis is a bacterial infection of the brain or spinal cord. It usually occurs in people who have had untreated syphilis for many years. Symptoms might include headache, difficulty coordinating muscle movements, paralysis, sensory deficits, and dementia.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis
diagnoses.description: Temporal arteritis is an inflammation of blood vessels, typically the temporal arteries, causing headache, vision disturbances, jaw pain when chewing, and sometimes symptoms of a stroke, such as weakness on one side of the body.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: Vertebrobasilar insufficiency is a condition resulting from reduced blood flow in the arteries at the back of the brain. Symptoms can include vision problems, dizziness, headache, difficulty speaking, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a minibar, a temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain, potentially causing aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain that can lead to various symptoms including aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that may present with visual disturbances, and rarely, aphasia and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, caused by infection or an autoimmune response, leading to symptoms including aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus caused by an infection in the brain that can cause aphasia, headache, and weakness among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves, potentially leading to symptoms like aphasia, weakness, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain Aneurysm
diagnoses.description: A bulge in a blood vessel in the brain that can leak or rupture, causing severe headache, aphasia, and weakness if it bleeds.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions, associated with abnormal electrical activity in the brain. It can sometimes present with aphasia and weakness post-seizure.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain and spinal cord membranes, typically caused by an infection. Symptoms can include headache, fever, stiffness, weakness, and in severe cases, aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by visual disturbances (such as scotoma), sensory symptoms (such as parasthesia and numbness), and sometimes difficulty speaking. These symptoms typically precede the headache phase.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around nerve fibers, causing inflammation and often leading to debilitating symptoms, including visual disturbances, numbness, weakness, and parasthesia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it presents with temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. Symptoms can include scotoma, parasthesia, and numbness. Unlike a stroke, the symptoms usually disappear within a few minutes to a few hours.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal cells growth in the brain can lead to pressure and various symptoms depending on the tumor’s location. Symptoms can include headaches, numbness, parasthesia, and visual disturbances like scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. High blood sugar (glucose) can injure nerves throughout your body. Diabetic neuropathy most often damages nerves in your legs and feet. Symptoms can include numbness, parasthesia, and pain.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the bacterium Borrelia burgdorferi. If left untreated, the infection can spread to the joints, heart, and nervous system, leading to a wide range of symptoms including headaches, facial palsy, numbness, and parasthesia.

diagnoses.name: Optic Neuritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the optic nerve that can cause a temporary reduction in vision. Symptoms include visual disturbances such as scotoma, pain with eye movement, and sometimes headache.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when the body does not have enough vitamin B12. It can cause neurological issues, including numbness and parasthesia in the hands and feet, muscle weakness, and problems with vision such as scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. Meningitis can cause headaches, fever, and a stiff neck, and if severe, can lead to neurological problems such as numbness and seizures.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by an abnormally low level of blood sugar (glucose). It's often related to the treatment of diabetes. Hypoglycemia can cause a variety of symptoms, including headache, numbness, and tingling of the mouth and fingers.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by visual disturbances and auras, often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it temporarily blocks blood flow to the brain, causing symptoms similar to a stroke.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain cells to die.

diagnoses.name: Benign Positional Vertigo
diagnoses.description: A vestibular disorder causing brief episodes of mild to intense dizziness associated with moving the head in certain positions.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, tinnitus, hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease affecting the brain and spinal cord, leading to weakness, coordination, balance difficulties, and other problems.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Any intracranial tumor resulting from abnormal and uncontrolled cell division, either in the brain itself, the cranial nerves, the brain envelopes, skull, pituitary and pineal gland, or metastases from elsewhere.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions, associated with abnormal electrical activity in the brain.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that may or may not cause a headache but includes dizziness, balance problems, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Posterior Circulation Ischemia
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by the narrowing or blockage of the arteries that supply blood to the back part of the brain, leading to symptoms such as vertigo, double vision, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden weakness, numbness, difficulty speaking, headache, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple Sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms can include fatigue, numbness and weakness, coordination and balance issues, and problems with vision.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Migraines are a neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound. Migraines can cause significant pain for hours to days and might be so severe that the pain is disabling.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is sometimes known as a mini-stroke. It is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage. Symptoms can include weakness, numbness, confusion, changes in vision, and difficulty speaking.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, problems with vision, vomiting, and mental changes.

diagnoses.name: Optic Neuritis
diagnoses.description: Optic neuritis is inflammation that damages the optic nerve, a bundle of nerve fibers that transmits visual information from your eye to your brain. Pain and temporary vision loss in one eye are common symptoms of optic neuritis. It is often associated with multiple sclerosis.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis
diagnoses.description: Temporal arteritis, also known as giant cell arteritis, is an inflammatory disease affecting the large blood vessels of the scalp, neck, and arms. It causes headaches, jaw pain, vision problems, and sometimes scalp tenderness.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barré Syndrome is a rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: Diabetic neuropathy is a type of nerve damage that can occur if you have diabetes. High blood sugar (glucose) can injure nerves throughout your body. Diabetic neuropathy most often damages nerves in your legs and feet. Symptoms can include numbness, loss of sensation, and pain.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A subarachnoid hemorrhage is bleeding in the space between the brain and the surrounding membrane (the subarachnoid space). It's often caused by the bursting of a small berry-shaped aneurysm. Besides sudden, severe headache, it might result in decreased levels of consciousness and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease characterized by acute and chronic inflammation of various tissues of the body. Common symptoms include malar rash, oral ulcers, and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Discoid Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the skin, causing scaly red patches that may lead to postinflammatory dyspigmentation.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease affecting the blood vessels, associated with lupus, that can cause skin lesions such as chilblains and rashes.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that displays features of lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including hemolytic anemia and oral ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints but can also cause systemic symptoms including anemia and skin manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that produce saliva and tears, but can also cause systemic complications like hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, including oral ulcers and various skin lesions.

diagnoses.name: Churg-Strauss Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A small and medium vessel vasculitis, associated with asthma and eosinophilia, which can manifest with skin lesions and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemia
diagnoses.description: A condition associated with hepatitis C infection and characterized by the presence of abnormal proteins in the blood, leading to vasculitis, skin manifestations like purpura, and potentially anemia.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash, including heliotrope rash around the eyes and Gottron's papules on the hands, but can also present with systemic features like hemolytic anemia.
